  "clarification": "Only go one level deep — each element of the outer list is assumed to be a list, and you collect their contents. Example: flatten([[1, 2], [3, 4]]) → [1, 2, 3, 4]. If an inner list contains further lists, leave them as-is: flatten([[1, [2]], [3]]) → [1, [2], 3].",
  "reference_solution": "def flatten(lst):\n    return [item for sublist in lst for item in sublist]\n"
